dataIdInfo.idPurp: Spatial depicition of ecological sites and states.
dataIdInfo.idAbs:
A draft polygon shapefile depicting states within ecological sites for the Jornada Experimental Range.

The first ecological site listed (esite) is the 'best fit' ecological site. The second ecological site listed (esite_alt) is the 'second best fit,' and is used when there is uncertainty as to ecological site or where more than one ecological site occurs within the polygon (e.g., undulating depth to petrocalcic horizon causing Shallow Sandy and Sandy ecological sites to vary over short distances). The third ecological site listed (esite_alt2) is either the 'third best fit,' and is used when there is uncertainty as to ecological site or where more than one ecological site occurs within the polygon.

The state map code (state_code) consists of two or three digits.

Two digit codes are as follows:

10 = exotic dominated

11 = Roads

12 = Tanks/Water hole

13 = Agricultural field

Three digit codes are the vegetation states in order of dominance. More than one number is used for a polygon where a polygon contains more than one vegetation state, and the vegetation state patches are too small to delineate/digitize. The first code in the three-number sequence best describes the dominant state of the polygon. The second number in the three-number sequence is the second-most common state. The last number in the three number sequence is the least common state. A zero is used in the second or third when only one or two states are found in the polygon.

Each number corresponds to the following state:

1 = grassland (HCPC state)

2 = altered grassland

3 = shrub/tree savanna (shrubs/succulents and grasses; HCPC state)

4 = shrub/tree-invaded grassland

5 = shrub/tree dominated

6 = shrubland or woodland

7 = bare (with or without annuals)

8 = gallery forest (HCPC state)

9 = exotic invaded

Topology errors have been corrected where there were overlapping polygons or gaps in polygons. Fields not part of the state map template have been removed (see workflow described below). Polygons with Dom species were cross-checked against field data points and corrected or removed where relevant.

L. Burkett recommends visiting soil map units correlated to the Clayey ecological site to determine if Clayey, Bottomland, or other ecological site.

Data workflow under E. Ayers:

Geodatabase was generated by using "ecosites_from_nasis_soils" as the input feature and JERbndry_N83 as the clip feature resulting in shapefile Jornada_Ecological_Sites as the output feature. Jornada_Ecological_Sites.shp was then exported into "ecosites_from_nasis_soils"/In_Progress/ to create geodatabase Jornada_Ecological_Sites. Previoulsy a geodatabase, Template2011_21Feb, was created to standardize fields in the attribute table for all states mapping efforts. Additional fields in the attribute table expanded the template to include data from ground truthing endeavors. Data from Jornada_Ecological_Sites geodatabase was loaded into Template2011_21Feb /In_Progress/Jornada_SNM_Ecosites. Then [Jornada_SNM_Ecosites] was copied and renamed JER to be used for digitizing ecological state polygons without disturbing the "parent" lines.Ongoing ecological state mapping has evolved a geodatabase chronological naming scheme to provide for a descriptive title for the most current version of the state map. Template2011_21Feb /In_Progress/Jornada_SNM_Ecosites has been abandon as the location for the geodatabase. The Template2011_21Feb fields have been retained and augmented so the Jornada_Ranch_States_1_30_2017 incorporates ground truth data from a spatial joins with MODIS, MURV, Goolsby, Seed Bank Study and Traverse_Points_jer_veg_2016.

2842 ecological state polygons were digitized during phase 1 of state mapping. Validating and attributing ecological state polygons is an ongoing phase 2 process. Ecological state map includes ground truth data gained from MODIS (Jeb Williamson), MURV (Laura Burkette) and Goolsby (Derrick Goolsby) to aid attributing. Additional ground truth data from Seed Bank Study (Kirsten Romig) and Vegetation Mapping (Eldon Ayers) further enhanced accuracy of the ecological site and ecological state values.
